Thread of anecdotes about John Swartzwelder: the last true libertarian and the man who inspired the Ron Swanson character in "Parks and Recreation", the mind behind "The Simpsons"

The start of his career involved him sending a signed joke submission to "Late Night with David Letterman" without attaching his address. The show writers had to trace him back and finally contacted him through his mother.

John Swartzwelder is one of the most elusive writers in modern history, even more so than Thomas Pynchon. At one point his fans actually were wondering if he truly existed or if he was a fake persona invented by the writers of Simpsons.

Little is known about his politics except that he is a "very conservative libertarian" and probably the only person in the world who is openly an anti-environmentalist.

An anecdote about him says that once he spent half an hour giving a speech on the benefits of deforestation.

As a writer on "The Simpsons" he did not stay in the office, but instead wrote the scripts in a nearby coffee shop while "drinking copious amounts of coffee and smoking endless cigarettes". After the anti-smoking law, he bought the diner booth and reinstalled it in his house.

After being rumored to be taking part in a documentary about a certain Simpsons episode, it was revealed that his participation consisted of confirming that he is a real, living person and saying the episode was "a good one".

During a documentary, he was called and asked what he was doing (if I remember correctly this was done either very early in the morning or in the small hours of the night). He responded that he was cooking steak.

He has not participated in the audio commentaries on The Simpsons despite being asked multiple times.

He was asked to make a brief joke appearance, in which he is asked if he wants to take part in the commentaries, to which he would respond with "No".

He refused to do it.
